questions.question_text: In probability and statistics, what is probability?

options.A: A numerical measure of the central tendency of a dataset, calculated by summing all values and dividing by the total count.
options.B: A numerical measure of how far a data point lies from the mean, expressed as a value between $-1$ and $1$.
options.C: A numerical measure of the likelihood that an event will occur, expressed as a value between $0$ (impossible) and $1$ (certain).
options.D: A numerical measure of the frequency of an event in a dataset, expressed as a count of occurrences rather than a ratio.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is the mean of a dataset?

options.A: A quantity representing the center of a collection of numbers, calculated by selecting the value that appears most frequently.
options.B: A quantity representing the spread of a collection of numbers, calculated by finding the difference between the maximum and minimum.
options.C: A quantity representing the center of a collection of numbers, calculated by sorting the values and selecting the middle one.
options.D: A quantity representing the center of a collection of numbers, calculated by summing all values and dividing by the count.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is the median of a dataset?

options.A: The most frequently occurring value in a dataset, representing the peak of the distribution.
options.B: The middle value that separates the higher half from the lower half when the data are arranged in order.
options.C: The middle value between the maximum and minimum of a dataset, calculated as their arithmetic average.
options.D: The average value obtained by summing all observations and dividing by the total number of data points.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is the mode of a dataset?

options.A: The value located at the exact center of a sorted dataset; it splits the data into two equal halves.
options.B: The value that appears most often in a set of data values; a dataset may have one mode, multiple modes, or no mode.
options.C: The value that appears least often in a set of data values; every dataset has exactly one unique mode.
options.D: The value obtained by summing all data points and dividing by the count; it represents the arithmetic average.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what does variance measure about a dataset?

options.A: The expected value of the linear deviation from the mean, measuring the direction in which numbers tend to spread.
options.B: The expected value of the squared deviation from the mean, measuring how far a set of numbers are spread out from their average.
options.C: The expected value of the absolute deviation from the median, measuring how far a set of numbers are spread from the center.
options.D: The expected value of the squared deviation from the mode, measuring how far a set of numbers cluster around the peak.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is the standard deviation?

options.A: A measure of the central tendency in a dataset, equal to the square root of the mean, denoted by $\mu$.
options.B: A measure of the amount of variation in a dataset, equal to the square root of the variance, denoted by $\sigma$.
options.C: A measure of the amount of skewness in a dataset, equal to the cube root of the variance, denoted by $\gamma$.
options.D: A measure of the amount of variation in a dataset, equal to the square of the variance, denoted by $\sigma^2$.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is a histogram?

options.A: A visual representation of the relationship between two variables using scattered points plotted on a coordinate plane.
options.B: A visual representation of the proportion of categories in a dataset using colored slices of a circular diagram.
options.C: A visual representation of the distribution of quantitative data using adjacent bars whose heights show the frequency of values in each bin.
options.D: A visual representation of trends in data over time using connected line segments plotted on a coordinate plane.

questions.question_text: In probability and statistics, what is a normal distribution?

options.A: A continuous probability distribution with an asymmetric right-skewed curve, defined by its median $\mu$ and variance $\sigma$.
options.B: A continuous probability distribution with a symmetric bell-shaped curve, defined by its mean $\mu$ and standard deviation $\sigma$.
options.C: A continuous probability distribution with a symmetric bell-shaped curve, defined by its variance $\mu$ and kurtosis $\sigma$.
options.D: A discrete probability distribution with a symmetric bell-shaped curve, defined by its mode $\mu$ and range $\sigma$.

questions.question_text: In probability and statistics, what is a random variable?

options.A: A mathematical function that assigns numerical values to each possible outcome in a sample space of a random process.
options.B: A mathematical function that assigns numerical values to each observed frequency in a data table of a random process.
options.C: A mathematical function that assigns categorical labels to each possible outcome in a sample space of a random process.
options.D: A mathematical constant that assigns numerical values to each possible outcome in a sample space of a deterministic process.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is a sample?

options.A: The complete set of all individuals in a statistical population, used to estimate characteristics of a smaller group.
options.B: A subset of variables selected from a statistical dataset, used to estimate the dimensionality of the whole population.
options.C: A subset of individuals selected from a statistical population, used to estimate characteristics of the whole population.
options.D: A subset of individuals selected from a statistical population, used to definitively determine all parameters of the population.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is correlation?

options.A: A statistical measure of the degree to which one variable predicts a nonlinear trend, ranging from $-1$ to $+1$.
options.B: A statistical measure of the degree to which two variables are causally related, ranging from $-1$ to $+1$.
options.C: A statistical measure of the degree to which two variables are linearly related, ranging from $-1$ to $+1$.
options.D: A statistical measure of the degree to which two variables are linearly related, ranging from $0$ to $+1$.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is an outlier?

options.A: A data point that differs marginally from neighboring observations in a dataset and can distort visual presentations.
options.B: A data point that differs significantly from other observations in a dataset and always indicates measurement error.
options.C: A data point that falls exactly at the mean of other observations in a dataset and can stabilize statistical analyses.
options.D: A data point that differs significantly from other observations in a dataset and can distort statistical analyses.

questions.question_text: In statistics, what is hypothesis testing?

options.A: A method of data visualization used to decide whether data provide sufficient evidence to reject a particular hypothesis.
options.B: A method of statistical inference used to decide whether data provide sufficient evidence to accept a particular hypothesis.
options.C: A method of statistical inference used to decide whether a sample provides exact proof to confirm a particular hypothesis.
options.D: A method of statistical inference used to decide whether data provide sufficient evidence to reject a particular hypothesis.

questions.question_text: In Bayes' theorem, what is the term $P(A)$ called, representing one's belief about event $A$ before observing evidence $B$?

options.A: The conditional likelihood, expressing the probability of evidence $B$ given that $A$ is true.
options.B: The marginal likelihood, expressing the total probability of observing evidence $B$ across all hypotheses.
options.C: The prior probability, expressing the initial degree of belief in $A$ before any evidence is considered.
options.D: The posterior probability, expressing the updated degree of belief in $A$ after evidence is considered.

questions.question_text: In null-hypothesis significance testing, what assumption must be true for a $p$-value to be calculated?

options.A: The null hypothesis must be assumed correct; the $p$-value is computed under that assumption.
options.B: The alternative hypothesis must be assumed correct; the $p$-value is computed under that assumption.
options.C: The effect size must be assumed nonzero; the $p$-value is computed under that assumption.
options.D: The sample size must be assumed infinite; the $p$-value is computed under that assumption.

questions.question_text: When a confidence level is written as $1 - \alpha$, what does the symbol $\alpha$ represent?

options.A: The margin of error, representing the maximum expected difference between the estimate and true parameter.
options.B: The confidence level, representing the probability that the interval does contain the true parameter.
options.C: The standard error, representing the average deviation of the sample mean from the population mean.
options.D: The significance level, representing the probability that the interval does not contain the true parameter.

questions.question_text: What is the name of the earliest version of the central limit theorem, which approximates the binomial distribution with a normal distribution?

options.A: The Lindeberg–Lévy theorem, which shows the binomial distribution approaches uniformity as $n$ grows.
options.B: The de Moivre–Laplace theorem, which shows the binomial distribution approaches normality as $n$ grows.
options.C: The Lyapunov stability theorem, which shows the binomial distribution approaches normality under skewness bounds.
options.D: The Berry–Esseen theorem, which shows the binomial distribution approaches normality with bounded error rates.

questions.question_text: The strong law of large numbers guarantees that the sample mean converges to the expected value in what specific sense?

options.A: Convergence in distribution, meaning the sample mean's distribution approaches the expected value's distribution.
options.B: Almost sure convergence, meaning the sample mean converges to the expected value with probability one.
options.C: Convergence in mean square, meaning the squared difference of sample mean and expected value approaches zero.
options.D: Convergence in probability, meaning the sample mean is likely close to the expected value for large samples.

questions.question_text: In the context of the binomial distribution, what is a single independent success-or-failure experiment called?

options.A: A geometric trial, which is an experiment with exactly two possible outcomes: continuation or termination.
options.B: A binomial trial, which is an experiment with multiple graded outcomes ranked by degree of success.
options.C: A Poisson trial, which is an experiment with exactly two possible outcomes: occurrence or nonoccurrence.
options.D: A Bernoulli trial, which is an experiment with exactly two possible outcomes: success or failure.

questions.question_text: What distinguishing property does the parameter $\lambda$ have in a Poisson distribution regarding its mean and variance?

options.A: The mean and variance are both equal to $\lambda$, making them identical for any Poisson-distributed variable.
options.B: The mean and variance are both equal to $\lambda^2$, making them identical but dependent on the squared rate.
options.C: The mean equals $\lambda$ and the variance equals $\lambda^2$, making the variance always larger than the mean.
options.D: The mean equals $\lambda$ and the variance equals $\sqrt{\lambda}$, making the variance always smaller than the mean.

questions.question_text: Student's t-test compares sample means when the population standard deviation is unknown. What distribution does the test statistic follow under the null hypothesis, and why is this distribution used instead of the standard normal?

options.A: The test statistic follows a Student's $t$-distribution with $n-1$ degrees of freedom, because estimating $\sigma$ from the sample introduces additional variability beyond the normal distribution
options.B: The test statistic follows an $F$-distribution with $(1, n-1)$ degrees of freedom, because the test is constructed as a ratio of two independent variance estimates
options.C: The test statistic follows a $\chi^2$ distribution with $n-1$ degrees of freedom, because the squared deviations from the sample mean are summed to estimate variability
options.D: The test statistic follows a standard normal $N(0,1)$ distribution regardless of sample size, because the Central Limit Theorem guarantees normality of the sample mean

questions.question_text: Pearson's chi-squared test evaluates whether observed categorical frequencies differ significantly from expected frequencies. What is the form of its test statistic?

options.A: $\chi^2 = \sum_i \frac{(O_i - E_i)^2}{E_i}$, where $O_i$ are observed counts and $E_i$ are expected counts under the null hypothesis
options.B: $\chi^2 = \sum_i (O_i - E_i)^2$, where the squared differences between observed and expected counts are summed without any normalizing denominator
options.C: $\chi^2 = \sum_i \frac{(O_i - E_i)^2}{O_i}$, where $O_i$ are observed counts and $E_i$ are expected counts, dividing by the observed rather than expected frequencies
options.D: $\chi^2 = \sum_i \frac{(O_i - E_i)}{E_i}$, where $O_i$ are observed counts and $E_i$ are expected counts, summing the signed deviations

questions.question_text: In simple linear regression, the model $Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \varepsilon$ is fit to data using ordinary least squares (OLS). What quantity does OLS minimize to estimate the parameters?

options.A: OLS minimizes the maximum residual $\max_i |y_i - \hat{y}_i|$, ensuring that no single observation has an excessively large prediction error
options.B: OLS minimizes the sum of squared residuals $\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i - \hat{y}_i)^2$, the total squared vertical distance between observed and predicted values
options.C: OLS minimizes the sum of squared horizontal distances between each data point and the regression line, measured parallel to the $x$-axis
options.D: OLS minimizes the sum of absolute residuals $\sum_{i=1}^{n}|y_i - \hat{y}_i|$, the total absolute vertical distance between observed and predicted values

questions.question_text: The expected value of a discrete random variable $X$ quantifies its long-run average. Which formula correctly defines $E[X]$ for a discrete distribution with probability mass function $P(X = x_i)$?

options.A: $E[X] = \prod_i x_i \, P(X = x_i)$, the product of each possible value weighted by its probability
options.B: $E[X] = \sum_i x_i / P(X = x_i)$, each possible value divided by its probability, then summed over all outcomes
options.C: $E[X] = \sum_i x_i \, P(X = x_i)$, the sum of each possible value weighted by its probability
options.D: $E[X] = \sum_i P(X = x_i) / n$, the average of the probability values divided by the number of possible outcomes

questions.question_text: Conditional probability measures how the likelihood of event $A$ changes when event $B$ is known to have occurred. What is the standard definition of $P(A \mid B)$?

options.A: $P(A \mid B) = \frac{P(A \cup B)}{P(B)}$, the probability of either event occurring divided by the probability of the conditioning event, where $P(B) > 0$
options.B: $P(A \mid B) = P(A) \cdot P(B)$, the product of the two individual event probabilities, which holds for all pairs of events
options.C: $P(A \mid B) = \frac{P(A \cap B)}{P(B)}$, the probability of both events occurring divided by the probability of the conditioning event, where $P(B) > 0$
options.D: $P(A \mid B) = \frac{P(B)}{P(A \cap B)}$, the probability of the conditioning event divided by the probability of both events occurring simultaneously

questions.question_text: In frequentist hypothesis testing, the null hypothesis $H_0$ serves as the default claim tested against an alternative. What does a Type I error represent in this framework?

options.A: A Type I error is rejecting $H_0$ when it is actually false (a true positive), and its probability equals the statistical power $1 - \beta$
options.B: A Type I error is rejecting $H_0$ when it is actually true (a false positive), and its probability is bounded by the significance level $\alpha$
options.C: A Type I error is failing to reject $H_0$ when it is actually true (a correct decision), and its probability equals $1 - \alpha$
options.D: A Type I error is failing to reject $H_0$ when it is actually false (a false negative), and its probability is denoted by $\beta$

questions.question_text: In Bayesian inference, the posterior is computed as $P(H \mid E) = \frac{P(E \mid H) \cdot P(H)}{P(E)}$. What role does $P(E)$ play, and why is it often hard to compute?

options.A: $P(E)$ is the posterior predictive probability of future data, requiring sampling from the joint distribution of all latent variables.
options.B: $P(E)$ is the likelihood of data given the hypothesis, requiring computation of the log-posterior gradient, which is numerically unstable.
options.C: $P(E)$ is the prior probability of the hypothesis, requiring specification of a conjugate prior distribution, which is unavailable for complex models.
options.D: $P(E)$ is the marginal likelihood, a normalizing constant requiring integration of the likelihood over all hypotheses, which is often intractable.

questions.question_text: In hypothesis testing, the probability of a Type I error is $\alpha$ and Type II error is $\beta$. What is statistical power and how does it relate to these error rates?

options.A: Power equals $\alpha + \beta$, the total probability of any decision error. Decreasing $\alpha$ also decreases $\beta$, so both can be minimized simultaneously.
options.B: Power equals $1 - \beta$, the probability of correctly rejecting a false null. Decreasing $\alpha$ generally increases $\beta$, so the two error rates trade off.
options.C: Power equals $\alpha \cdot \beta$, the joint probability of both errors at once. Increasing sample size raises both $\alpha$ and $\beta$, reducing power.
options.D: Power equals $1 - \alpha$, the probability of correctly retaining a true null. Decreasing $\beta$ generally increases $\alpha$, so the two error rates trade off.

questions.question_text: In logistic regression, the model is $\log\frac{p}{1-p} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x$. How is $\beta_1$ interpreted in terms of odds, and what function converts log-odds to probability?

options.A: A one-unit increase in $x$ multiplies the probability by $\beta_1$. The identity link $p = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x$ maps the linear combination to probability.
options.B: A one-unit increase in $x$ adds $\beta_1$ directly to the probability. The probit function $\Phi(\beta_0+\beta_1 x)$ maps the linear predictor to probability.
options.C: A one-unit increase in $x$ adds $e^{\beta_1}$ to the log-odds. The softmax function $\frac{e^{\beta_0+\beta_1 x}}{\sum e^{\beta_j}}$ maps log-odds to probability.
options.D: A one-unit increase in $x$ multiplies the odds by $e^{\beta_1}$. The logistic function $p = \frac{1}{1+e^{-(\beta_0+\beta_1 x)}}$ maps log-odds to probability.

questions.question_text: A probability density function $f(x)$ describes a continuous random variable. Why can $f(x)$ exceed 1 at certain points, and how is the probability over an interval $[a,b]$ obtained?

options.A: $f(x)$ gives probability per unit length, not probability itself, so it can exceed 1. Probability over $[a,b]$ is $\int_a^b f(x)\,dx$.
options.B: $f(x)$ gives cumulative probability up to $x$, not density, so it can exceed 1. Probability over $[a,b]$ is $f(b) - f(a)$.
options.C: $f(x)$ gives conditional probability at a specific outcome, not marginal probability, so it can exceed 1. Probability over $[a,b]$ is $\sum_{x=a}^{b} f(x)$.
options.D: $f(x)$ gives the likelihood ratio relative to a reference distribution, not probability, so it can exceed 1. Probability over $[a,b]$ is $\frac{f(a)+f(b)}{2}$.

questions.question_text: Covariance is defined as $\text{Cov}(X,Y) = E[(X - \mu_X)(Y - \mu_Y)]$. Why is covariance alone insufficient for comparing association strength across different variable pairs?

options.A: Covariance only captures nonlinear relationships. Squaring it gives the coefficient of determination, unitless and bounded between $0$ and $1$.
options.B: Covariance measures only strength, not direction. Taking its absolute value gives Kendall's tau, unitless and bounded between $0$ and $1$.
options.C: Covariance depends on the variables' units and scales. Normalizing by both standard deviations gives the correlation coefficient, unitless and bounded between $-1$ and $1$.
options.D: Covariance requires normally distributed variables. Taking its logarithm gives Spearman's rank coefficient, unitless and bounded between $-1$ and $1$.

questions.question_text: The law of total probability states $P(A) = \sum_n P(A \mid B_n)P(B_n)$. What condition must events $\{B_n\}$ satisfy, and how does this connect to Bayes' theorem?

options.A: The $\{B_n\}$ must be mutually exclusive and collectively exhaustive (a partition). This law provides the denominator $P(A)$ in Bayes' theorem via marginalization.
options.B: The $\{B_n\}$ must be positively correlated and jointly normal. This law provides the likelihood $P(B_n \mid A)$ in Bayes' theorem via integration.
options.C: The $\{B_n\}$ must each exceed probability $0.5$ and overlap pairwise. This law provides the prior $P(B_n)$ in Bayes' theorem via averaging.
options.D: The $\{B_n\}$ must be independent and identically distributed with equal probability. This law provides the numerator $P(A \mid B_n)$ in Bayes' theorem via conditioning.

questions.question_text: The maximum likelihood estimator is asymptotically efficient. What does this mean in terms of a well-known lower bound, and what quantity determines the asymptotic variance of the MLE?

options.A: The MLE achieves the Cramér–Rao lower bound as $n \to \infty$. Its asymptotic variance is the inverse of the Fisher information, $I(\theta)^{-1}$.
options.B: The MLE achieves the Chebyshev lower bound as $n \to \infty$. Its asymptotic variance is the inverse of the score function, $S(\theta)^{-1}$.
options.C: The MLE achieves the Cramér–Rao lower bound as $n \to \infty$. Its asymptotic variance is the inverse of the likelihood ratio, $\Lambda(\theta)^{-1}$.
options.D: The MLE achieves the Cramér–Rao lower bound only for finite $n$. Its asymptotic variance is the inverse of the Hessian of the prior, $\pi''(\theta)^{-1}$.

questions.question_text: A discrete-time Markov chain has the property that its future state depends only on the present state. What two conditions on the chain guarantee convergence to a unique stationary distribution $\pi$?

options.A: The chain must be recurrent (every state is revisited infinitely often) and aperiodic (the GCD of return times to each state is 1).
options.B: The chain must be irreducible (every state reachable from every other) and aperiodic (the GCD of return times to each state is 1).
options.C: The chain must be ergodic (every state has finite expected return time) and symmetric (the transition matrix equals its transpose).
options.D: The chain must be irreducible (every state reachable from every other) and reversible (detailed balance holds for each pair of states).

questions.question_text: In one-way ANOVA, the total sum of squares is partitioned as $SS_T = SS_B + SS_W$. What does the $F$-statistic compare, and what does a large $F$-value suggest about the group means?

options.A: The $F$-statistic is the ratio of between-group mean square to total mean square. A large $F$ suggests group variances differ more than expected by chance.
options.B: The $F$-statistic is the ratio of between-group mean square to within-group mean square. A large $F$ suggests group means differ more than expected by chance.
options.C: The $F$-statistic is the ratio of within-group mean square to between-group mean square. A large $F$ suggests group means differ more than expected by chance.
options.D: The $F$-statistic is the ratio of between-group sum of squares to within-group sum of squares. A large $F$ suggests the residuals are non-normally distributed.

questions.question_text: The moment-generating function of a random variable $X$ is defined as $M_X(t) = E[e^{tX}]$. How is the $n$-th moment of $X$ obtained from $M_X(t)$, and what key uniqueness property does the MGF possess?

options.A: Compute $E[X^n] = \ln M_X^{(n)}(0)$, the $n$-th derivative of the log-MGF at $t=0$. If the MGF exists near zero, it uniquely determines the distribution.
options.B: Compute $E[X^n] = M_X^{(n)}(0)$, the $n$-th derivative at $t=0$. If the MGF exists near zero, it uniquely determines the distribution.
options.C: Compute $E[X^n] = M_X^{(n)}(1)$, the $n$-th derivative at $t=1$. If the MGF exists near zero, it uniquely determines the distribution.
options.D: Compute $E[X^n] = M_X^{(n)}(0)$, the $n$-th derivative at $t=0$. The MGF must exist for all real $t$ to determine the distribution.

questions.question_text: A statistic $T(X)$ is sufficient for parameter $\theta$ if the data provide no additional information about $\theta$ beyond $T$. What does the Fisher–Neyman factorization theorem state about the joint density $f(x; \theta)$?

options.A: $f(x;\theta)$ factors as $g(x, \theta) \cdot h(T(x))$, where $g$ depends on data and $\theta$ jointly and $h$ depends only on $T$.
options.B: $f(x;\theta)$ factors as $g(T(x), \theta) \cdot h(x)$, where $g$ depends on data only through $T$ and $h$ is free of $\theta$.
options.C: $f(x;\theta)$ factors as $g(T(x), \theta) \cdot h(x, \theta)$, where $g$ depends on data only through $T$ but $h$ also involves $\theta$.
options.D: $f(x;\theta)$ factors as $g(T(x)) \cdot h(x, \theta)$, where $g$ depends only on $T$ and $h$ captures all dependence on $\theta$.

questions.question_text: The bootstrap, introduced by Bradley Efron, estimates the sampling distribution of a statistic. What resampling procedure defines the nonparametric bootstrap, and what does it approximate?

options.A: Draw repeated samples of size $n$ with replacement from the observed data. This approximates the sampling distribution of the statistic without assuming a parametric model.
options.B: Draw repeated samples of size $n$ with replacement from the observed data. This approximates the posterior distribution of the parameter under a noninformative prior.
options.C: Draw repeated samples of size $n$ without replacement from the observed data. This approximates the sampling distribution of the statistic without assuming a parametric model.
options.D: Draw repeated samples of size $n/2$ with replacement from the observed data. This approximates the permutation distribution of the test statistic under the null hypothesis.

questions.question_text: The Cramér-Rao bound gives the minimum variance for unbiased estimators. Under what condition does an unbiased estimator achieve equality in the bound, and what is the score function's form?

options.A: Equality holds when the score $\frac{\partial \log f}{\partial \theta}$ is quadratic in $\hat{\theta}(x)$, which occurs precisely for exponential family distributions.
options.B: Equality holds when the score $\frac{\partial \log f}{\partial \theta}$ is linear in $\hat{\theta}(x)$, which occurs precisely for exponential family distributions.
options.C: Equality holds when the Hessian $\frac{\partial^2 \log f}{\partial \theta^2}$ is linear in $\hat{\theta}(x)$, which occurs precisely for exponential family distributions.
options.D: Equality holds when the score $\frac{\partial \log f}{\partial \theta}$ is linear in $\hat{\theta}(x)$, which occurs for any distribution with finite variance.

questions.question_text: Kolmogorov's third axiom requires $\sigma$-additivity rather than mere finite additivity for disjoint events. What structural requirement does this impose on the event space, and what key property does it enable?

options.A: The event space must be a $\sigma$-algebra, enabling uniform convergence of the probability measure: $\sup_A |P_n(A) - P(A)| \to 0$ for monotone sequences.
options.B: The event space must be a $\sigma$-algebra, enabling absolute continuity of the probability measure: $P(A) = 0$ whenever the Lebesgue measure $\mu(A) = 0$.
options.C: The event space must be an algebra closed under finite unions, enabling continuity of the probability measure: $P(\lim_n A_n) = \lim_n P(A_n)$ for monotone sequences.
options.D: The event space must be a $\sigma$-algebra, enabling continuity of the probability measure: $P(\lim_n A_n) = \lim_n P(A_n)$ for monotone event sequences.

questions.question_text: The optional stopping theorem states $E[X_\tau] = E[X_0]$ for a martingale stopped at $\tau$. Which sufficient condition on the stopping time ensures this holds, and why?

options.A: It suffices that $\tau \leq N$ a.s. for some constant $N$, and additionally the increments $|X_{n+1} - X_n|$ must be uniformly bounded.
options.B: It suffices that $E[\tau] < \infty$; finite expected stopping time alone always guarantees the result without further integrability conditions.
options.C: It suffices that $P(\tau < \infty) = 1$; almost sure finiteness alone guarantees the result without any further integrability conditions.
options.D: It suffices that $\tau \leq N$ a.s. for some constant $N$; no further integrability condition beyond the martingale property is then needed.

questions.question_text: In the exponential family canonical form $f(x|\theta) = h(x)\exp[\eta(\theta)\cdot T(x) - A(\theta)]$, the log-partition function $A(\theta)$ encodes key information. What do its first and second derivatives with respect to natural parameters yield?

options.A: The first derivative $\nabla_\eta A$ gives $E[T(x)]$, and the Hessian $\nabla^2_\eta A$ gives the Fisher information $I(\theta)$ directly in the original parameterization.
options.B: The first derivative $\nabla_\eta A$ gives the mode of $T(x)$, and the Hessian $\nabla^2_\eta A$ gives the covariance matrix $\mathrm{Cov}[T(x)]$ of the sufficient statistic.
options.C: The first derivative $\nabla_\eta A$ gives $E[T(x)]$, and the Hessian $\nabla^2_\eta A$ gives the covariance matrix $\mathrm{Cov}[T(x)]$ of the sufficient statistic.
options.D: The first derivative $\nabla_\eta A$ gives $E[x]$ directly, and the Hessian $\nabla^2_\eta A$ gives $\mathrm{Var}[x]$ rather than the sufficient statistic's covariance.

questions.question_text: A Gaussian process is fully specified by its mean and covariance functions. What distinguishes Gaussian processes from general stochastic processes regarding wide-sense versus strict-sense stationarity?

options.A: For Gaussian processes wide-sense stationarity implies strict-sense only in the special case of zero mean and unit variance at every index.
options.B: For Gaussian processes strict-sense stationarity implies wide-sense but not conversely, exactly as for general stochastic processes with finite moments.
options.C: For Gaussian processes the two notions are equivalent only when the mean function is identically zero and the covariance kernel is translation-invariant.
options.D: For Gaussian processes the two notions are equivalent, because all finite-dimensional distributions are fully determined by the first two moments.

questions.question_text: The Rao-Blackwell theorem improves an estimator by conditioning on a sufficient statistic $T(X)$. What is the MSE decomposition, and what additional condition on $T(X)$ guarantees the result is UMVUE?

options.A: MSE decomposes as $E[(\delta_1-\theta)^2] = E[(\delta-\theta)^2] - \mathrm{Var}(E[\delta|T])$. If $T$ is also complete, Lehmann-Scheffé guarantees UMVUE.
options.B: MSE decomposes as $E[(\delta_1-\theta)^2] = E[(\delta-\theta)^2] - E[\mathrm{Var}(\delta|T)]$. If $T$ is also ancillary, Lehmann-Scheffé guarantees UMVUE.
options.C: MSE decomposes as $E[(\delta_1-\theta)^2] = E[(\delta-\theta)^2] - E[\mathrm{Var}(\delta|T)]$. If $T$ is minimal sufficient, Lehmann-Scheffé guarantees UMVUE.
options.D: MSE decomposes as $E[(\delta_1-\theta)^2] = E[(\delta-\theta)^2] - E[\mathrm{Var}(\delta|T)]$. If $T$ is also complete, Lehmann-Scheffé guarantees UMVUE.

questions.question_text: The Neyman-Pearson lemma constructs the most powerful test for simple $H_0$ vs simple $H_1$ at significance level $\alpha$. When the likelihood ratio $\Lambda(x)$ exactly equals the critical threshold $\eta$, how is the test defined to achieve exact size $\alpha$?

options.A: A deterministic test is used: at $\Lambda(x) = \eta$, always reject, which guarantees the test achieves exact size $\alpha$.
options.B: A randomized test is used: at $\Lambda(x) = \eta$, reject with probability $\gamma$ calibrated so the test achieves exact size $\alpha$.
options.C: A truncation rule is used: at $\Lambda(x) = \eta$, exclude the observation and recompute the test to achieve exact size $\alpha$.
options.D: A randomized test is used: at $\Lambda(x) = \eta$, reject with probability equal to $\alpha$ so the test achieves exact size $\alpha$.

questions.question_text: Sklar's theorem guarantees that any multivariate joint distribution can be decomposed using a copula. What specific property of the Gaussian copula regarding tail dependence makes it potentially dangerous for modeling joint extreme events in finance?

options.A: The Gaussian copula has nonzero upper tail dependence but zero lower tail dependence for $\rho \in (-1,1)$, systematically underestimating only joint negative extreme events.
options.B: The Gaussian copula has symmetric nonzero tail dependence proportional to $|\rho|$ for $\rho \in (-1,1)$, systematically overestimating the probability of simultaneous extreme events.
options.C: The Gaussian copula has zero upper and lower tail dependence for any correlation $\rho \in (-1,1)$, systematically underestimating the probability of simultaneous extreme events.
options.D: The Gaussian copula has zero upper and lower tail dependence only when $\rho = 0$, otherwise capturing joint extremes correctly for moderate correlations.

questions.question_text: In the stick-breaking construction of a Dirichlet process $\mathrm{DP}(H, \alpha)$, weights $\beta_k$ are built from i.i.d. draws $\beta'_k \sim \mathrm{Beta}(1, \alpha)$. How are the atoms $\theta_k$ chosen, and what happens to the weight distribution as $\alpha \to 0$?

options.A: Atoms are drawn i.i.d. from $H$. As $\alpha \to 0$, weights decay geometrically with ratio $\alpha$, concentrating mass on finitely many atoms.
options.B: Atoms are drawn from the posterior predictive. As $\alpha \to 0$, $\beta_1 \to 1$ almost surely, so all mass concentrates on a single atom.
options.C: Atoms are drawn i.i.d. from $H$. As $\alpha \to 0$, weights become uniform across infinitely many atoms, producing a continuous distribution.
options.D: Atoms are drawn i.i.d. from $H$. As $\alpha \to 0$, $\beta_1 \to 1$ almost surely, so all mass concentrates on a single atom.

questions.question_text: Donsker's theorem extends the Glivenko-Cantelli theorem by establishing a functional central limit theorem for the empirical process $\sqrt{n}(F_n - F)$. What is the limiting stochastic process, and what distinguishes a Donsker class from a Glivenko-Cantelli class?

options.A: The limit is a Brownian bridge $B(F(x))$. Donsker classes require almost sure convergence to a Gaussian limit, equivalent to uniform a.s. convergence for Glivenko-Cantelli classes.
options.B: The limit is a Brownian bridge $B(F(x))$. Donsker classes require weak convergence to a Gaussian limit, strictly stronger than uniform a.s. convergence for Glivenko-Cantelli classes.
options.C: The limit is standard Brownian motion $W(F(x))$. Donsker classes require weak convergence to a Gaussian limit, strictly stronger than uniform a.s. convergence for Glivenko-Cantelli classes.
options.D: The limit is a Brownian bridge $B(F(x))$. Donsker classes require pointwise convergence to a Gaussian limit, strictly weaker than uniform a.s. convergence for Glivenko-Cantelli classes.

questions.question_text: Fisher information $\mathcal{I}(\theta)$ equals the negative expected second derivative of the log-likelihood under regularity conditions. If one reparametrizes from $\theta$ to $\eta = g(\theta)$ where $g$ is a smooth bijection, how does the Fisher information transform?

options.A: It transforms as $\mathcal{I}_\eta(\eta) = \mathcal{I}_\theta(\theta) \cdot \left|\frac{d\theta}{d\eta}\right|$, so Fisher information rescales by the absolute Jacobian determinant.
options.B: It is invariant: $\mathcal{I}_\eta(\eta) = \mathcal{I}_\theta(\theta)$ for any smooth bijection $g$, which is why Fisher information defines a canonical metric.
options.C: It transforms as $\mathcal{I}_\eta(\eta) = \mathcal{I}_\theta(\theta) \cdot \frac{d\theta}{d\eta}$, so Fisher information rescales linearly by the Jacobian.
options.D: It transforms as $\mathcal{I}_\eta(\eta) = \mathcal{I}_\theta(\theta) \cdot \left(\frac{d\theta}{d\eta}\right)^2$, so Fisher information is not reparametrization-invariant but rescales by the squared Jacobian.

questions.question_text: The Pickands-Balkema-de Haan theorem provides the theoretical basis for the peaks-over-threshold method in extreme value analysis. What distribution does it identify for exceedances above a high threshold $u$, and how does this relate to the generalized extreme value distribution?

options.A: Exceedances converge to the generalized Pareto distribution (GPD), whose shape parameter $\xi$ equals the reciprocal of the corresponding GEV shape parameter for block maxima.
options.B: Exceedances converge to the generalized Pareto distribution (GPD), whose shape parameter $\xi$ matches that of the corresponding GEV distribution for block maxima.
options.C: Exceedances converge to the generalized Pareto distribution (GPD), whose shape parameter $\xi$ equals the negative of the corresponding GEV shape parameter for block maxima.
options.D: Exceedances converge to the Gumbel distribution, whose location parameter matches the shape parameter of the corresponding GEV distribution for block maxima.
